In this report, ABAH ADAH writes on power sector reform and supply of electricity to rural communities to boost rural development The minister of state, Power, Goddy Jedy Agba, has said that Nigerians living in rural communities need steady and regular supply of electricity to earn daily income as majority are involved in small scale businesses that require the use of electricity, especially artisans, technicians and food vendors. Speaking at a media briefing in Abuja, he expressed concern that consumers of electricity in the urban areas are not ready to pay for supply, saying the rural dwellers are more committed to pay for consumption at any point in time, making their demand for electricity more elastic than the urban dwellers. The minister argued that the federal government under the President Muhammadu Buhari’s administration is committed to ensuring that rural electrification is given top priority to create electricity environmental friendly relations between government and the rural communities. “Business will grow if the people have light, we are working hard to ensure that, but we need to work harder, and the essence of this interaction is for the media and Nigerians to assess our performance, the National Assembly is worried,other Nigerians are worried about the state of power in the country, and we are committed to see to the workability of the sector. “I feel that we should give those people in rural communities more than we give attention to ourselves in the city because you grow from down to up, and if we grow, then we will grow our nation,” he said. However, major actors in the power sector including the managing director of Rural Electrification Agency (REA), Ahmed Salihujo, director general, National Power Institute of Nigeria (NAPTIN), Nagode Ahmed and the managing director, Nigerian Electricity Management Services Agency (NEMSA) were at the board room media briefing alongside the minister of state, Power, Goddy Jedy Agba, where national and rural issues concerning regular supply of electricity were debated and solutions proffered going forward. Each of the Heads of Agencies present at the event took time to give detail accounts of how the generation, transmission and distribution of electricity can be improved, though they all agreed that the major constrain is with the distribution companies who have not showed enough commitment in funding the distribution network of the value chain. Part 9, section 88 number 9 of the Electric Power Sector Reforms Act states that the rural electrification agency was created for the expansion of Grid, the development of isolated and mini-grid system and renewable energy power generation, which of course the Rural Electrification Agency is implementing the Nigerian Electrification Project (NEP), Engineering Economic Initiative (EE), Engineering Education Programme (EEP), Rural Electrification Fund (REF), Energy Data Base and Capital Projects. Private sector partnership is pivotal to driving the mandate of REA, NAPTIN and NEMSA, the three agencies that its top officials sat together a few days back to take a critical look on how the power sector reforms can achieve the supply component and deliver to the people adequately on the use of electricity. The policy thrust of government to deliver on its promises in all sectors has always been brilliant, though the implementation strategy has always been faulty, because of political and systemic sabotage, but the focus of the recent assembly of experts and actors in the sector by the minister of state, power brought to the fore the commitment and doggedness on the part of the federal government to light up communities in Nigeria. The minister’s position is that no Nigerian living in either the rural area or urban centres should stay without electricity, knowing very well that the provision and supply of electricity is the foundation of economic development in Nigeria and any other country for that matter, being a boost to industrialisation and top class manufacturing. Concept papers on procured equipment, metering, and other power installation status were made bare to demonstrate capacity in the direction of its sectorial reforms targeted at making sure there is electricity in all homes and small scale enterprises. According to the director general NAPTIN, the Mambilla project is capable of employing over 50, 000 Nigerians, through road construction and welding. Others are electricians and technicians, direct and indirect employment in the areas of trading activities in technical wares, food vending and the services of other basic essentials in the area. He posited that the ongoing power sector reforms in the country has trained over 16, 000 Nigerians and intakes from sister countries with the intent to build capacity and invent on new methods of rendering effective and efficient supply of electricity within the rural communities and urban areas. Experts have argued that the sector is about to experience a boost if all technical inputs and government commitment is not misplaced in the implementation process, which according to them has been the bane of sectorial development, where sentiments and self is given topmost priority as against public interest and public good. It was estimated that over 80, million Nigerians do not have electricity, the consequences of this absence is low productivity and low income generation around communities, the interface has provided an opportunity for the public to understand the reasons why it has been fairly difficult to have steady supply, even though there are assurances that the power situation will improve in a moment. The sector if optimally functional will promote investment; stimulate growth, as the World Bank has offered a grant of $350 million to boost rural electrification proramme, it is a combined credit facility from the World Bank and the African Development Bank (AfDB), that provides performance based funds to developers for the deployment of mini-grids and solar home systems and the facilitation of productive use of equipment for residents in un-served and underserved communities. NEMSA, by its mandate has continued to regulate technical standards including the provision of meters, declaring sub-standard meters unsafe for use; this functionality has given impetus to the fact that certified meters passing the process of tests can be used by consumers where accurate billing system is sustained.